{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_2feininger_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280605037/1948081501/0143.xml":{"full_text":"Rate Increases Boost\nU. S. Telephone Bill\n$140,000,000 a Year\n\u2022y th\u00ab A\u00bbociot*d Pr\u00bbi\nNEW YORK, Aug. 14.\u2014America's\ntelephone bill has gone up with just\nabout everything else since the war,\nand is due to go up still more.\nThe *8,000,000,000 Bell System,\nworld\u2019s biggest utility, has been\ngranted since the war rate increases\ntotaling $140,000,000 a year, it is\nshown in an Associated Press sur\nvey made across the country.\nThe Bell System, which operates\nfour-fifths of the Nation's 36,000,000\ntelephones, says its costs are up\njust like everybody else\u2019s. It has\nbeen getting mo6t of the increases\nit has asked, but not without a\nstruggle In some cases.\nThese are the first general tele\nphone rate Increases in two decades\nor more, and they have stirred up\nhot opposition in several States.\nUtility commissions have made deep\nslashes in amounts asked and have\nturned their fire on some of the\noperation methods of the American\nTelephone Telegraph Co. and\nits subsidiaries that comprise the\nBell System.\nGranted in 36 States.\nThe increases already granted\naffect 36 States. In addition, Bell;\ncompanies have applications pend\ning for some $64,000,000 a year in\nrate boosts in 16 States, including\nseven in which no increases have\nyet been granted.\nThe country's 6,900 Independent\ncompanies, most of them small,\nalso have been getting increases\nand also have additional applica\ntions pending.\nThe boosts granted so far gener\nally have been greater on business\ntelephones and long distance calls\nwithin the States than on home\nservice. 1\nIn some localities, home rates\nwere left unchanged despite general\nincreases, but most were boosted\n25 or 50 cents a month and some\nas much as one dollar.\nBusiness telephone rates gener\nally went up 25 cents to $2.50 a\nmonth over old rates, with $2 in- j\ncreases fairly common. A few were!\nboosted as much as $3 and $3.25 a\nmonth, but these generally were;\naccounted for in part by other fac-!\ntors such as increased areas in j\nwhich nontoll calls could be made. j\nInterstate Rates Unchanged.\nNo increases have been granted\nor asked in interstate long distance\nrates, controlled by the Federal\nCommunications Commission. In\nfact, the FCC estimates interstate\nrates have been reduced nearly\n*131,000,000 a year since 1936.\nWith rate increases for Bell com\npanies granted or pending in 43\nStates, it is expected the list even\ntually will be joined by the other\nfive\u2014Delaware, Nevada, New York,\nNorth Dakota and Pennsylvania.\nA. T. T. President Leroy A.\nWilson recently told stockholders\nthat other applications will be made\nIn the near future.\u2019\u2019 They will be\nneeded, he said, to meet rising costs\nand keep the Bell System in a\nsound financial, position to continue\nits huge expansion program, and\nmaintain high standards of service\nto present customers.\nIn nine of the States in which in\ncreases were granted\u2014Including two\nwith no State regulation\u2014and ip\nthe District of Columbia, Bell com\npanies got the full increases they\nasked. In many others there was\nonly minor opposition and minor\ntrimming.\nAttacked in Some States.\nBut in some States the increases\nhave been attacked by State and\nmunicipal officials and private in\nterests as being too high. The most\ncommon arguments against both\nBell and independents have been\nthat lesser increases would provide\nfair returns on company investments\nand that, in areas not yet converted\nto dial operation, improved service\nshould be given in advance of rate\nIncreases.\nConsiderable commission nre has\nbeen directed against certain of the\nfinancial practices of the giant Bell\nSystem, and several commissions cut\n\u2022ubstantial amounts from Bell com\npany applications.\nOn the other hand, Bell com\npanies have been generally success\nful In the courts in case\u00bb in which\nthey contended commission cuts or\ndisallowances were confiscatory.\nCommission rulings involving more\nthan *13,000,000 a year in rate in\ncreases were upset in courts in\nGeorgia, Alabama, Mississippi, Okla\nhoma, New Hampshire and Ten\nnessee.\nCommission criticism of Bell com\npanies has centered largely on three\npoints:\n1. The license fee of one and one\nhalf per cent which A. T. and T.\nreceives on gross receipts of- its tele\nphone subsidiaries.\n2. The \"standard supply contract\u201d\nunder which Bell companies buy the\nmajor portion of their equipment\nfrom Western Electric, the A. T.1\nand T.'s manufacturing subsidiary.\n3 The rates A. T. and T. and the\naubsidiary companies pay for new\nmoney needed to finance their ex\npansion and improvement programs.\nFee Revision Demanded.\nA special telephone committee of\nthe National Association of State\nUtility Regulatory Commissions has\nasked A. T. and T. to revise the per\ncent license fee system. It says\n\"practically all State commissions\nhave severely criticized\" the per\ncentage system of charges for man\nagement services, advice and\nresearch.\nThe Bell System says the license\nfee plan results in \"new methods\nMISS NATION\u2019S CAPITAL\u2014Miss Ruth Smallwood, 21, of 302\nFairfax street, Falls Church, Va., is congratulated by Tommy\nDorsey, the orchestra leader, after he crowned her Miss\nNation's Capital 'at Chesapeake Beach, Md. She will receive\na week\u2019s vacation at Atlantic City for winning the beauty\ncontest. \u2014Seaboard Photo.\n'Madame Butterfly\u2019 Attracts\nRecord Water Gate Audience\nBy Alice Eversmon\nPuccini\u2019s '\u2019Madame Butterfly,\u201d\nrained out on Wednesday, was given\nlast night at the Water Gate before\na crowd that topped the audience\nrecord of the Lyric Opera Associ\nation\u2019s season so far. It also was\nthe best staged of the productions,\nthe many difficulties in scenic effect\nrequired in this opera being most\nskillfully overcome. Not overbur\ndened with attempts at elaborations,\nthe staging adhered to the require\nments as well as was possible on\nthe barge. This, together with the\nvariegated colors of the costumes,\ncreated a pleasing effect furthered\nby the excellent performance of the\nprincipal singers.\nThe first act moved somewhat\ncumbersomely and with less assur\nance than marked the final portion*\nof the opera. But Eugene Conley,\nfn the role of Pinkerton, infused life\ninto it through his fine singing and\nacting. His voice is a viril tenor\nand by his ability to put fire into\nwhatever he sings, carried the duet\nSMne with Butterfly to a splendid\nclimax. He was not given much\nassistance in this opening scene by\nEva DeLuca who took the part of\nButterfly after singing Violetta in\n\"Traviata\u201d for the second time the\nprevious night.\nOpportunities Missed.\nMiss DeLuca took hold of the\nrole much better in the second act\nand gave a moving and well-plapoed\nperfdrmance in the scene which\nmakes gruelling demands on the\nartist both vocally and interpre\ntively. She does not invest her por\ntrayal with much charm, and the\nnumerous opportunities of the first\nact to stress Cio-Cio-San\u2019s youth\nand naivete were not seized. But\nwhen it came to the more emotional\nunfoldment of the following act,\nof operation\u201d and \"improved types\nof plant and equipment.\u201d It says\nwasteful duplication of effort is\navoided, each company gets help\nin solving its own problems, and\nimprovements in the practices of\neach are made available to all. The\nservice, it contends, is cheaper than\nif it were obtained from independ\nent firms.\nBut some State commissions have\npointed out that any Increases\ngranted by them automatically\nboost A. T. and T. \"take\u2019\u2019 from the\nlicense fee without any correspond\ning increase in service to the sub\nsidiary. And they contend funds\npaid by subsidiary companies to\nA. T. and T. on a percentage basis\nbear no direct relation to the value\nof serivces received by the com\npanies.\nSupply Contract Questioned.\nOn the second point of criticism,\nseveral commissions questioned\nwhether prices charged to telephone\ncompanies by Western Electric were\nnot too high, but did not make\ndisallowances on that point. Their\nnational association is studying the\ncontract.\nThe Bell System contends the\nWestern Electric arrangement pro\nvides equipment at prices lower than\nthe operating subsidiaries would\nhave to pay if they bought from in\ndependent producers. It also con\ntends there are great advantages\nin standardization of equipment and\nin better planned production.\nOn the third point, some of the\ncommissions suggested the Bell\nSystem should get more of its new\nmoney for expansion through bonds\nbearing Low interest, rather thart\nthrough sale of stock or debentures\nconvertible to stock calling for a\nhigher rate of return on the money.\nA. T. and T. takes the position\nthat the greater the proponion of\ndebt capital a company has out\nstanding, the more it will have to\npay when it needs additional funds,\nand the greater return stock in\nvestors w ill demand because of their\ngreater risk. The company also\nsays the fixed charges represented\nby interest on bonds couid. if too\nhigh, become a dangerous liability\nduring a business depression.\nEnjoy Scenic Tours in Air-Coaled Comfort\nIt'* always fair weather in a Gray Line De Luxe Bus\nALL-DAY TOUR SKYLINE DRIVE\nTours on Tuesdays. Thursdays. Saturdays.\nSundays Most scenic and historic tour in the\nU S See Skyline Caverns. Skyline Drive.\nShenandoah National Park. Luncheon stop at\nSkyline Terrace Leave P:.'lO a m FA\nP-hour trip Fare includes taxes. .vU\nadmissions m\n2-DAY TOUR WILLIAMSBURG, VA.\nTours start Wednesdays. Saturdays Visit\nWilliamsburg and historic Colonial Virginia.\nTravel via famous Skyline Drive Visit Monti- j\ncello. Thomas Jefferson's home: stay overnight\nin Richmond. See Williamsburg s famous re\nstored buildings and gardens Re'urn via 1\nFredericksburg Leave am Fare in\ncludes hotel, meals, taxes, ad\nmissions and guide fees.\nReservations necessary\n$2850\nSr\u00bb Your Trovel Agent or coll\nDistrict 0600\nFor R\u00bb**rvotion#\nTHE GRAY LINE\nAIR-COOLED COACHES\u2014RECLINING SEATS\u2014ACCOMMODATIONS ASSURED\njshe was more in her element. She\nsang the music with good effect\nalthough here again, if her picture\nof the character had been stronger,\nshe could have warmed up her tonal\nquality considerably.\nIn point of feeling for the part,\nLydia Edwards gave a more rounded\npresentation. She was thoroughly\nin the role all the time and acted\nwith experience and finesse. In gen\neral, she and Mr. Conley seemed\nmore certain of the music and had\nless need of watching the conductor\ncontinuously. Angelo Pilotto gave\n;a capable delineation of Sharpless,\n'the American consul, although his\nvoice is not always secure enough\nfor a comfortable delivery of the\nmusic.\nImpersonation Praised.\nRalph Telasko as the Imperial\nCommissar and as Prince Yamadori\nshowed a real talent for impersona\ntion. In fact, most of the singers\nwho have taken the smaller roles\nin the operas of this festival have\ndone excellent work. John Rossi,\nwho was Goro, the marriage broker,\nMast night, has been invaluable and\nj Victor Tatozzi, with his height and\nmakeup, made the part of the Bonze\nas clearly defined as he has other\nroles. The cast was completed by\nDee Sherman as Kate Pinkerton\nand a charming unnamed child,\nwho appeared as Butterfly's son.\nThe conductor, young Nicholas\nRescigno, had trouble putting life\ni into the orchestra in the first act\nJ and in guiding the, slightly unsure\nchorus. Later the* lempo moved\nalong with more spirit and he\nmanaged to bring out the special\nfeatures in the orchestral score\n.tellingly. The deficiencies did not\naffect the overall finish of the per\nformance which, considering all\nthat is involved in the staging of\n\u2022'Butterfly,\u201d was one of the best\n'seen in some time here.\nGirl, 14, Dies From Fire\nSet by Lightning\nBy the Associated Press\nHAGERSTOWN, Md\u201e Aug. 14\nElsie Ocker, 14-year-old daughter\nof Mr. and Mrs. John Ocker, died\ntoday in Washington County Hos\npital of burns suffered when light*\nj ning set fire to her homeThursday.\nMrs. Ocker, who also was burned\nin the -.blaze that destroyed the\nhouse, was described by hospital\nphysicians as being in very good\ncondition despite \u201cpaainful bums\non her right shoulder and right\nleg.\"\nMr. Ocker, 35, an airplane me\nchanic, who worked for 18 months\nin his spare time to build the house,\nwas slightly burned on his right\narm while fighting the fire. The\nseven other Ocker children were\nunhurt.\nNash Post No. 8 Elects\nW. E. Ritter Commander\nW. E. Ritter has been elected\ncommander of Kenneth H. Nash\nPost No. 8, American Legion and\nwill be Installed during ceremonies\nat 8:30 p.m., September 8, in the\nNash Clubhouse. 223 D street S.E.\nMr. Ritter succeeds James Wright.\nOther new officers for the coming\nyear are A. T. Thompson, first vice\ncommander; C. J. Piper, second vice\ncommander: Cornelius Moerdyk,\nthird vice commander; Ray Miller,\nsergeant at arms; Otis Jones,\nchaplain; W. D. Mulkey, judge ad\nvocate. and Edward Hancock, quar\ntermaster.\n42 New Faces in House\nAnd Nine in Senate\nAssured Next Year\nfty the Associated Frost\nDeaths, primary defeats, volun\ntary retirements, and ambition to\ntry for other political office have\nalready assured 42 new faces in\nthe .House and nine in the Senate\nnext year.\nA Compilation yesterday showed\n24 Democratic and 18 Republican\nHouse seats being vacated for vary\ning reasons. Four Democratic and\nfive Republican Senators also are\nleaving the Washington scene re\ngardless of the outcome of the No\nvember elections.\nSeven Democratic members of the\nHouse have suffered primary de-1\nfeats so far as against four Repub-:\nlicans.\nThe sevea Democrats are Jarman'\nand Manasco, Alabama: Price,;\nFlorida: Meade, Maryland; Mrs.\nLusk, New Mexico; Peden, Okla\nhoma and Courtney, Tennessee (The\nHouse Democratic Campaign Com\nmittee says the result in Mr. Court\nney\u2019s race was so close there prob\nably will be a contest).\nFour Republicans Defeated.\nThe four Republican defeats were\nGwynne, Iowa, and Gallagher, I\nChadwick, and Scoblick. Pennsyl\nvania.\nNine Democrats and seven Re\npublicans decided not to run again.\nThe Democrats: Cravens, Arkansas;\nLea and Elliott, California: Hen\ndricks, Florida: Bell, Missouri; Fol\nger and Clark, North Carolina: West,\nTexas, and Flannagan, Virginia. Re\npublicans: Dirksen, Johnson and\nClippenger. Illinois; Lewis, Ken\ntucky; Mathews and Hartley, New\nJersey, and Ellsworth Buck, Netv\nYork.\nTwo House Democrats have been\ndefeated trying for Senate nomina\ntions: Glen Johnson, Oklahoma,\nand Dorn, South Carolina.\nEach party has four House mem\nbers seeking to transfer to the Sen\nate or some State office. Democrats:\n|Harless, Arizona, is running for\nGovernor, and Chapman, Kentucky;\nKefauver, Tennessee, and John\nson, Texas, are seeking Senate\nseats.\nThree Republicans, Mrs. Smith,\nMaine; Rizley. Oklahoma, and\nMundt, South Dakota, are trying\nfor the Senate. A fourth, Stratton,\nis out for Secretary of State of Illi\nnois.\nNoble Johnson Named Judge.\nOne Republican, Noble Johnson,\nIndiana, has been named to the\nFederal bench. And there are two\nHouse vacancies in each party: Re\npublican, old Illinois 7th and 21st\nDistricts; Democrat, Missouri 10th\nand Virginia 6th.\nWith 33 Senate seats to be filled\nNovember 2 (ttfo in Louisiana),\nover one-fourth are certain to be\noccupied by newcomers, because:\nTwo Democrats, Stewart, Tennes\nsee, and Umstead, North Carolina,\nhave been defeated for nomination.\nTwo others. Hatch, New Mexico, and\nO'Daniel, Texas, are retiring. Five\nRepublicans, Bushfield, South Da\nkota; Capper, Kansas; Hawkes, New\nJersey (who withdrew aft$r the\nState pkrty drgdnlzation dehied him\nsupport i: Moore, Oklahoma, and\nWhite, Maine, are retiring.\nHammerstein\n(ContSfeecf Pregi First PagcA\nMr. Garvey died ft few hours later\nin a Tijuana hospital. Paul Carr,\nUnited States vice-consul in\nTijuana, was arranging for trans\nfer of the bodies across the border.\nMexican highway patrolmen said\nthe heavy, expensive sedan driven\nby Mr. Kays swung around the\ncurve at high speed and crashed\ninto a south-bound car driven by\nAngel Saad Andres of Ensenada.\nMr. Kays' car then careened off the\nhighway and rolled down a steep\nenbankment.\nMr Kays and Miss Hammerstein,\nwho was the daughter of Arthur\nHammerstein, New York State pro\nducer and impresario, were mar\nried in Los Angeles 22 years ago.\nDuring the 1920s, Miss Hammer\nstein was starred in Columbia's\n\"SOS Perils of the Sea.\u201d Others\nshe played in included \u2018\u2018Rupert of\nHentzau,\u201d sequel to \u201cThe Prisoner\nof Zenda\"; \u201cBroadway Gold,\u201d\n\"Greater Than Fame,\u201d \"One Glori\nous Night\u201d and \u201cDrums of Jeop\nardy.\u201d\nGrandfather Built Opera House.\nHer grandfather was Osca: Ham\nmerstein, New York producer who\nalso produced several popular plays\nat Covent Garden in London. When\nhe returned to New York he built\nthe world's largest opera house.\nMr. Garvey's parents operated a\n20,000-acre ranch at Garvey He\nwas a native o.\" Los Angeies and\n[attended St. Vincent\u2019s College and\nwas graduated f\u2019om Columbia Unl\n1 versity\u2019s Law School.\nHis father, Richard Garvey, sr\u201e\nwas associated with the famous E.\nJ. (Lucky) Baldwin, early day Cali\nfornia developer. The Garvey ranch\n;has been sub-divided into the towns\nof Monterey Park and Wilmar,\nCalif.\nNewfoundland produced over 125,\n000.000 pounds of salt codfish last\nI year.\nA Modern bPljOllt\n1 Gas Furnace*\nTo be GIVEN to the owner\nof the oldest gas heating\nunit in the D. C.\nMetropolitan Area!\n'PLUS Chronotherm Thermostat thot\noutomaticolly turns heat up tor day,\ndown tor night.\nJust phone us or mail a Post Card to\nDept. HC-2 for rules and entry blank.\nOur Engineer will moke a free survey\nfor you.\nOffer effective August 15-September 30.\nATTENTION COAL USERS:\nUnder certain conditions gas is\navailable to you. Phone us for more\ninformation.\nS;: I iiSajrfgji\nI* Fully Automatic\nFully Guaranteed\nOne-Day Installation\nJohn G. Websteb\nPLUMBING HEATING APPLIANCES\n(EiUbltihrd 1915)\n\u201cWashington\u2019s Specialist in Gas Heat\u201d\n627 F ST. N.W. EX. 4615\nQ\u00bb. TU Heckt C\u00bb. an F St.\nOPEN SATURDAYS\nCured Alcoholic\nTo Hear His Own\nSymphony Played\nBy th\u00ab Associated Press\nDETROIT, Aug. 14.\u2014A former\nmental patient, nursed back to\nhealth by listening to music, will\nhear a nationally famous orchestra\nplay this week part of a symphony\nwhich he helped compose.\nErnest Salisbury, 25, was classi\nfied as an alcoholic when he was\ntaken to the mental ward of a\nDetroit hospital two years ago.\nThere he was given an unusual\ntreatment which had worked won\nders with other mental patients.\nThe medicine was music.\nDuring his stay in the hospital,\nSalisbury began to compose music.\nSince his release he has continued\nthe study of music, and now has\nwritten or helped write 150 pieces.\nThe Detroit Symphony, directed\nby Valter Poole, will play the first\nmovement of his \u2018\u2018Elolse Symphony\u201d\nThursday night.\nCo-composer of the work with\nSalisbury is Dr. Ira Altshuler, the\nman who administered treatments\nto him. Subject of the symphony is\na mental hospital.\nGeorge Richardson,\nNats' Treasurer, Dies\nFuneral arrangements were beng\nmade last night for George M.\nRichardson, 70, treasurer ot the\nWashington baseball club, who died\nFriday night at his home in Pitman,\nN. J.\nMr. Richardson had been treas\nurer of the Nationals since 1941,\nafter the death of his twin brother,\nWilliam; who was vice president of\nthe club..\nGeorge Richardson, although a\nbehind-the-scenes partner in the\nNationals, did not appear often at\nthe ball park and rarely took an ac\ntive part in the club's affairs. He\nhad planned, however, to attend the\nceremonies at the stadium Tuesday\nnight when public tribute will be\npaid to Mr. Griffith.\nIn tribute to Mr. Richardson, the\nflag at Griffith Stadium was at half\nstaff yesterday during the game be\ntween Washington and Boston.\nAt his death, Mr. Richardson was\nvice president of the Merchants\nWarehouse Co., and the Girard\nWarehouse Co., both treasurer of the\nNational Portland Cement Co., and\npresident of the Philadelphia Ex\nport Co., all of Philadelphia.\nSurvivors include his widow,\nEthel; his mother, Dr. Emma E. M.\nRichardson, a Camden, N. J. phy\nsician; a brother, Edward, of Phila\ndelphia and two daughters and a\nson, all of pitman.\nHarvester Strike Due\nTomorrow Midnight\nBy th* Associated Press\nSPRINGFIELD, Ohio, Aug. 14\nExecutive Board members of CIO\nUnited Auto Workers Local 402 to\nnight announced the International\nHarvester plant here will be struck\nat midnight Monday unless a con\ntract agreement is reached.\nBoard members also said there\nwould be simultaneous walkouts at\nHarvester plants In Melrose Park,\n111., and Evansville and Port Wayne,\nInd.\nThe union said there would be\nno work wittmut contract. The\npresent contract expires at jnldnight\nMonday.\nThe Springfield plant employs\n4,700, of which 3,400 are members\nof the UAW. The local authorized\nthe boafd last night to call a strike\n\"if necessary.\u201d\n\"Be on the job Monday,\u201d the\nExecutive Board notified local\nmembers, \u201cbut the few who work\nthe ow'l shift that night should be\nprepared to quit at midnight.\u201d\nThe union struck the plant here\nin 1941 in a wage dispute.\nUAW and company representa\ntives failed to reach an agreement\ntoday during a six-hour meeting at\nChicago. The session was recessed\nuntil tomorrow.\nMan Sought in Robbery\nAnd Beating of Junk Dealer\nPolice last night still sought a\nman who beat and robbed a Wash\nington junk dealer of $5,000 in cash\nand checks early yesterday.\nThe victim was Aaron C. Sells, 49,\nof 1410 Taylor street N.W., who was\nassaulted at the entrance of his\nshop at 1125 First street N.W. He\nsuffered severe bruises. The only\nsuspect picked up yesterday was re\nleased after questioning.\nPolice believed the assailant was\nwell acquainted with Mr. Sells' habit\nof bringing the Saturday payrolls\nwith him in a paper bag. The loot\nobtained was part cash and part\nin checks.\nWest Coast Maritime\nSettlement Unlikely,\nFact-Finders Report\nly th\u00ab Associated PrHi\nA White House fact-finding board\nreported yesterday that the pros\npects of settling a West Coast Mari\ntime dispute \u201cseem slim. Indeed,\u201d\nbut on the East Coast are \u201cvery\ngood.\u201d\nThe board made Its final report\nto President Truman under the na\ntional emergency provision of the\nTaft-Hartley Act.\nIt made no recommendations, bur\nmerely described the situation. The\ndispute over methods of hiring is\nstill the big barrier to a general\nagreement, it said.\nUnder the law, inquiry boards\nmust make up their final reports\n60 days after the issuance of an\ninjunction.\nElection Is Next Step.\nThe Justice Department blocked\nan all-coast strike of seamen and\ndock workers by getting court or\nders on June 14 at New York, Cleve\nland and San Francisco.\nThe board was headed by Harry!\nShulman of the Yale University Law\nSchool.\nNow that the fact-finders have\nreported, .the law requires that the\nNational Labor Relations Board\nconduct elections to determine\nwhether the workers wish to accept\nthe last offers made by the employ\ners. Such elections must be finished\nin 15 days.\nWithin five days after that (Sep\ntember 2 in this case) the injunc\ntions are supposed to be thrown out,\nleaving the union legally free to\nstrike if the vote has gone against\naccepting the employers\u2019 offers.\nHiring la First Problem.\nGovernment officials don't see\nhow the NLRB can conduct elections\nin such a short period with seamen\nscattered all over the oceans of the\nworld. Seven unions are involved,\nthe most important of which are\nCIO Longshoremen headed by Harry\nBridges and the CIO National\nMaritime Union headed by Joseph\nCurran.\nThe board said that in the West\nCoast dispute in which Bridges's\nunion plays a leading role, relations\n\"are characterized by bitterly hos\ntile Institutional and personal at\ntitudes\nOn the Pacific Coast, the board\nsaid, the controversy over hiring\npractices continues\u2019 as \u2018.\u2018the major\ncontroversy blanketing all others.'\nBy contrast, the board said that\non the East Coast, where Mr. Cur\nran\u2019s seamen play an important\npart, \"the parties appear to have\nmade earnest and effective effort\nto reach agreement.\"\nThe barrier of the hiring issue,\nsaid the board, has been removed\nby the expressed willingness of the\nemployers to continue the existing\n\"hiring halls\u201d\u2014by which the unions\nfurnish employes when needed\u2014\nuntil there is a judicial determina\ntion of their legality under the\nTaft-Hartley Law.\nSome bemands Withdrawn.\nThe board said the unions on the\nEast Coast have withdrawn a num\nber of their demands, tentative\nagreement has been reached on\nother issues, and the \u2018\u2018remaining\ndifferences are quite narrow \u201cwith\ngood prospect for a settlement in\nthe near future.\nThe board said the prospect is\nalso good with respect, to Alaska,\nwhere .the hiring hall lsstie has been\nsimilarly treated-and negotiations\nare continuing.\nThe board aaid that on .the Great\nLakes the employers do not bar\ngain jointly and \u201csome have already\nreached settlements. Others have\nmade offer# satisfactory to the\nunion in all respects except on the\nhiring issue, which continues to\nblock agreement.\u201d\nBoat Blast in Rhode River\nBadly Burns District Man\nA Washington man was badly\nburned yesterday afternoon when\ngasoline In his 16-foot motorboat\nexploded and set the craft on fire\nin Rhode River at Mayo, Md., about\n12 miles south of Annapolis.\nThe Injured man, Irvin'Thomas,\n22, of 1617 D street N.E., was taken\nto Emergency Hospital in Annapo\nlis. Three other persons in the boat\nwith him were uninjured. Police\ndid not get their names.\nAnne Arundel County police at\nGalesville, Md., said the explosion\napparently occurred when gas in the\nbilge of the boat ignited as Mr.\nThomas started the motor. The\nboat was only a few feet off shore\nat the time. The boat was de\nstroyed.\nUruguay expects to harvest twice\nas many peanuts this year as in\n1947,\nDespite government efforts to re\nlax credit, Ecuador has a business\nslump.\nAt Kill\u2019s\nyou con RENT.\na Brand New Piano\nThere is no reason now why\nyour child should wait to learn\nmusic. For as low as $10\nmonthly (plus delivery cost)\nyou can have a beautiful,\nmodern new piano in your\nhome.\nand you get\nfor as little as\nsin -si\nw delivery)\nm\u2022\nFull Allowanct If You Buy Within 6 Months\nIf. within 6 months you decide to buy the piano you\nare renting, full allowance will be made for the rental\ncharges against the purchase price. Remember, these\nare brand-new pianos, of the latest and most popular\nmodels.\nCompletely\nAir\nConditioned\nREpublie 6212\nPresbyterians to Issue\nChurch Teamwork Study\nfty lh> Auifint\u00bbd hw\nRICHMOND, Aug. 14.\u2014A\nblueprint for rood effective team\nwork by pasten,' Sunday School\nsuperintendents arid directors of re\nligious education will be issued soon\nby the training school of the Gen\neral Assembly of the Presbyterian\nChurch of the U. S. A., as a result\nof a detailed study by leaders in\nreligious education throughout the\nchurch.\nDr. Patrick N. Carmichael, dean\nof the faculty and director of the\nsummer session, said the blueprint\nwould be available to all denomina\ntions.\nLeaders in the field of religious\neducation from 15 synods through\nout the South participated in the\nwork of drafting the blueprint\nthrough answering detailed ques\u00bb\ntionnaires or representation in a\ntwo-week conference at the school.\nThe blue {Mint will endeavor to\ndefine areas of major responsibility\nfor the minister, the superintendent\nand the director of religious edu\ncation. The latter is an office which\nalmost all large churches of most\ndenominations have added to give\ndirection to the work through em\nployment of a trained worker.\nFrancis W. Hines Dies,*\nWas Navy Photographer\nFrancis W. Hines. 55, a photogra\npher employed at the David Taylor\nModel Basin at Carderock, Md.,\ndied unexpectedly yesterday at his\nhome. 1367 K street S.E.\nA native of Alexandria. Mr. Hines\nmoved to Washington as a young\nman. He entered the Army in\nWorld War I and remained in the\nservice for 17 years.\nExcept for a brief period of em\nployment as a photographer with\nthe Washington Daily News, Mt.\nHines had been with the Navy\ntesting basin since about 1940.\nHe is survived by his widow, Mrs.\nViolet Furr Hines; a son, F. W.\nHines, jr., of New York, and two\nsisters. Mrs. Virginia Garmon and\nMrs. Nina Stott of Washington.\nFuneral services will be held at\n3 p.m. Tuesday in Fort Myer Chapel.\nBurial will be in Arlington Ceme\ntery.\nIllegal Drug Traffic\nIs Growing Despite\nIncreased Arrests\nly th* Auockit\u00abd Pr\u00abM\nThe micit drug traffic 1* still\ngrowing, although more persons are\nbeing arrested as violators, the\nTreasury reported yesterday.\nNarcotics of the opium-cocalne\nheroin types seized during the 12\nmonths ended June 30 totaled 6,755\nounces, compared with 6,091 ounces\nin the preivous year.\nApproximately 40.000 ounces of\nmarijuana was captured in the fiscal\nyear, about twice the amount seized\nduring the year before.\nCigarettes Seized.\nApproximately 17.000 marijuana\ncigarettes were seized in the last 12\nmonths, 8,000 more than were taken\nin 1947.\nDuring the last fiscal year 3.180\npersons were arrested by the Bu\nreau of Narcotics, compared with\n2,855 in 1947.\nBoth the Bureau of Narcoties and\nthe Customs Bureau handled the\nnarcotics work.\nThe Treasury said the seized\ndrugs included heroin from Turkey,\nItalian morphine, Peruvian cocaine,\nLebanese hashish. Indian an<f Iran\nian opium, African marijuana or\n\"Dagga\" and Tunisian \"Takrouri\"\nor marijuana.\nMexico Important Source.\nThe Customs Bureau said Mexico\nis still an important source of sup\nply for smugglers of illicit dope\nalthough Turkey has assumed\ngreater relative importance.\nThe bureau said raw opium seized\nat Atlantic Coast ports in mast\ncases originated in Turkey, India\nand Iran with Marseilles and Le\nHavre in France as Important\ntransit ports.\nThe largest haul was 55 pounds\nof raw opium found aboard the\nBritish ship Silverlarch at Boston\nand New York, the Treasury said.\nMexico will spend $6,400,000 in\nmodernizing its telecommunications\nsystem.\nThieves took $50,000~hidden in an\nauto tire by a Sydney (Australia)\nracketeer.\nCORNER\nCABINETS\nMade for fine quality U4\" thick\nclear white pine with back of\nplywood. Makes an Ideal dis\nplay center for your cholca\nchina and glassware.\n$57.5\u00b0\nKnocked Down\n\u00bb\u201ci\u201c *6500\nHardware\nFree Delivery\nOther Cabinets Afode-to-Order\nEISINGER\nMILL fr tUMBER CO.\n473* Bethesdo A*e. Wl. 6300\n\n-t\nWant Me to Drive,\nYou \u00a9eer to\nSee That House?\nA\n\u201cI\u2019ll be waiting at the office Sunday, 1-5 p.m. for 1\nyour call. The entire Bernstein sales staff will be\nthere to drive you to any of the many fine homes we\noffer FOR SALE. No obligation, of course. A few\nof these homes are in today\u2019s classified section.\u201d\nLeo liimi Co\nREALTORS\n1415 K St. N.W. MEtropoliton 5400\n^J^INSIST ON QUALITY^\nRE-UPHOLSTERING\nand RE-DESIGNING\nBEAT THE RUSH!\nNew Fabrics Are Now in!\nOrder NOW for Choicest\nSelection of Fabrics and\nGREATEST SAVINGS\nBe wise! Customize 